communications.subject: Your UNC-Chapel Hill public records request #25-807 has been submitted.
communications.communication:
UNC-Chapel Hill ************************************************************************ Your record request #25-807 has been submitted successfully. The University processes requests as promptly as possible and, generally, in the order they are received. Broader and more vague requests (for example, “all documents,” "all names," or “all emails” covering an indefinite time period) will likely receive a request for clarification prior to any collection or review of records.  Because of the large volume of requests and a legal mandate to review every page to protect confidential information, it often takes time before we can start processing a new request. We post all public records requests to nextrequest.unc.edu. For more information about the public records process at UNC-Chapel Hill, visit https://nextrequest.unc.edu/faqs.    Sincerely,   The Public Records Office The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill ************************************************************************ Reply to this email or sign in to contact UNC-Chapel Hill.

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Thomas Henschel interaction reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Regarding an interaction with Thomas Henschel on 01/25/2013:
- All incident, dispatch log entries and arrest reports. Incident reports and case records refer to reports produced with notes and narratives, a description of what happened by the responding officer, trace reports, case notes and litigation files
- All unedited body-worn camera / bodycam recordings. I am specifically requesting the unedited body-worn camera recordings captured by all officers present for the full duration of the incident, including audio recordings associated with the footage. If any portion of the requested footage must be redacted, I ask that you clearly indicate the portions that have been redacted and provide an explanation of the legal basis for the redactions
- All 911 or calls for service logs, audio and transcripts
- All computer aided dispatch (CAD) reports and a copy of your department’s dispatch 10 signals/codes, agency dispatch signals/codes and CAD signals/codes

I request these records in their native digital formats and not in formats that degrade the accessibility of the records, such as tabular data converted to PDF or Word files. If converting the native digital format to another high-fidelity format, such as CSV or Excel, please take care not to introduce formatting inconsistencies or errors, which can occur in the conversion process (for example, encoding errors or the inclusion of internal unescaped quotation marks in CSV files). Should the records above represent certain values as numeric codes or abbreviations that are not self-explanatory, I additionally request all records necessary to interpret those codes and abbreviations.

I am a member of the news media. The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

Production of Responsive Records on a Rolling Basis: In the event that a portion of the present request is completed before the full request is completed, I ask that the records be produced on a rolling basis.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sarah Hopkins

title: SC DHEC Request, Septic System Records, 140 & 150 W. Main St. Pacolet, SC 29372

communications.subject: South Carolina Public Records Law Request: SC DHEC Request, Septic System Records, 140 & 150 W. Main St. Pacolet, SC 29372
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the South Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

As per South Carolina Freedom of Information Act (§ 30-4-10 et seq.), I am requesting copies of all records related to the onsite wastewater (septic) system serving the following properties in Pacolet, SC:

1. 140 W Main St. Pacolet, SC 29372 – Parcel # 3-33-03-009.03

2. 150 West Main St. Pacolet, SC 29372  Main Building – Parcel # 3-33-03-009.04

3. 150 West Main St., Suite B (metal building), Pacolet, SC 29372  – Parcel # 3-33-03-009.04

Please include for each property:

- Any permits, approvals, or inspections conducted by SC DHEC for the septic system(s) serving these addresses.

- Any “Permit to Construct” or “Approval for Use” documents for the system(s).

- Any records showing septic system design, capacity, and its intended use.

- Any records approving additional plumbing fixtures or changes in use that would increase wastewater flow.

If the septic system serving these addresses is a shared system, please also provide all records for the shared system as a whole.

If no records exist for any of the above addresses or for the shared system, please provide written confirmation of that fact.

If any portion of this request is denied, please cite the specific exemption under FOIA that justifies the refusal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Greg Samsa

communications.subject: Your Appalachian State University public records request #25-141 has been submitted.
communications.communication:
Appalachian State University ************************************************************************ Your record request #25-141 has been submitted successfully. Appalachian State University has received your request for public records. We would like to inform you about the procedures we adhere to when processing public records requests. Reviewing Procedure: Upon receipt of each request, we diligently review them in the order they arrive. Our main objective is to identify any records that align with your specific request. It's essential to understand that under the North Carolina Public Records Act, the university is not mandated to produce new records to satisfy a public records request. Because of the large volume of requests and a legal mandate to review every page to protect confidential information, it often takes time before we can start processing a new request. The broader and more vague the request the longer it takes to identify and collect potential records. Please identify individual names, departments or vendors. The Public Records Office is unable to fulfill requests for "all e-mails", "all documents", “all [insert job title]” across nearly 50,000 email addresses, as such a search would include accounts not subject to GS 132. Exclusions to Right of Access: There exist numerous statutes within the General Statutes that exempt certain records from public access. A brief overview of some of the most pertinent exceptions includes: * Personnel Records: While we protect most public employee details, some information such as name, age, salary, salary history, contract terms, original employment date, title, and hire date can be disclosed. All other details are deemed confidential. * Trial or Court Preparation Materials * Trade Secrets * Closed-Session Minutes Or Account of Closed-Session Minutes * Personal Identifying Information: Access is restricted to information that might lead to identity theft. * Records Involving Security * Contract Bid Documents & Construction Diaries: Until a contract is awarded, details about informal construction or purchase bids remain undisclosed. * Telephone Numbers Held By 911 Systems * Emergency Response Plans * Detailed plans and Drawings of public buildings and Infrastructure Framework for Public Records Disclosure: Only records that currently exist and pertain to public business will be disclosed. There is no obligation on our part to create or compile a non-existent record. While a majority of our records are related to business matters, there are significant exceptions to this rule. Any vague, overreaching, or burdensome request will not only be subjected to extended compliance times but may also be denied outright. The involvement of multiple parties or entities further complicates and elongates this process. For exhaustive demands, we reserve the right to levy fees to recuperate the considerable costs of record searching and duplication. Any reluctance or refusal to cover these charges can and will lead to delays or outright refusal in record delivery. Payments are required in advance of any release. Ensure you are specific and precise in your requests to avoid unnecessary expenses. For records relating to students, under the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA), the university is obligated to ensure the privacy of student education records. Thus, student contact information and educational records remains undisclosed as per University Policy 105.2. Athletic Contracts can be found here. https://appstatesports.com/sports/2018/2/21/athletics-head-coach-ad-contracts.aspx Media representatives may contact the Office of University Communications with media inquiries here. https://uc.appstate.edu/media Visit https://appstate.nextrequest.com for information on fees that may be charged to cover the cost of producing public records. If, upon reviewing these guidelines, you believe your request might not be in alignment, we kindly request that you consider withdrawing it. For a more in-depth understanding, you can review the Appalachian State University's Public Records policy here. http://policy.appstate.edu/Public_Records_Requests. Feel free to contact us if you have any questions. Thank you.   The Public Records Team Appalachian State University     ************************************************************************ Reply to this email or sign in to contact Appalachian State University.
